eventName: Give a little to those who give a lot - Macmillan Cancer Support
pageSummary: Going dry (no alcohol) for 6 weeks because we want to say thank you
pageSummaryWhy: we want to say thank you
story:
Thanks for supporting this fundraising effort. Ian and I are so grateful for any contributions you can make to help us reach our target  

Macmillan Cancer Support is there to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. We know from a loved one’s recent experience what a huge difference this can make.

We decided to give up alcohol for 6 weeks to show our support for a very special person undergoing 6 weeks of cancer treatment. And while we had the easier challenge we were surprised by how much money we saved (!) and it felt only right to donate that money to this very worthwhile charity.  While we chose to give up the G and T’s and glasses of wine and donate that cost saving, a few friends suggested opening this page for others to donate too. It would be great if you would like to help us say thank you for the wonderful care this organisation offers.

story:

Sammy loved life and enjoyed it and she was taken too soon. All our thoughts are with her family at this time.

eventName: Band of brave baldies to be
story:
Hi from Chris Phillips and Swithin Fry! Our life long mate Pete Biggs, who now lives in Vancouver, was recently diagnosed with a brain tumour. He has just completed a course of Radiation Therapy and is loosing his hair.

Swithin, who now lives in Catalonia, thought that a great way to show solidarity with Pete would be to shave his head and I have foolishly agreed to join him!

We both have family and friends who have reason to be grateful for the support of cancer charities and thought that we’d ask you to make our shaving worthwhile and donate money to   cancer charities listed below.

We plan to shave our heads on Monday 30th November. Could we raise £1000 by that date?

BC Charity Foundation

Macmillan Cancer Charity

Lliga Contra El Cancer ( The main cancer charity in Catalonia )

West Park Cancer Charity ( A Sheffield based cancer charity )

We will of course post updates of our haircuts and bald heads! Please give generously!

story:
In May of 2019 I was diagnosed with Acute Lymphoblastic Leukaemia. This resulted in me undergoing chemotherapy for 16 weeks while unable to leave the hospital. After that I was given a short break before being brought back into hospital to have more intense radiotherapy and chemotherapy before having a bone marrow transplant. This was the most difficult year of my life for both my family and myself. I am still currently recovering and along with my family and friends would like to show our appreciation to Macmillan through this fundraiser. Thanks to Macmillan we were all able to receive support in various forms even continuing long after my stay in hospital.


For this event I will be livestreaming a few different games with some of my friends, hoping to raise funds to help a charity that has done so much for us already.

pageSummary: I will be running 5k for 10 days because we need to keep supporting research and treatment.
pageSummaryWhat: I will be running 5k for 10 days
pageSummaryWhy: we need to keep supporting research and treatment.
story:
At the start of lockdown I decided to purchase a running machine. Not for running but for walking. After time, out of know where I turned up the speed and found myself running. I used the opportunity of lockdown to get myself in better shape. Not just for fitness but my well-being. During my time running I had made myself a promise to put my achievement to better use but what? Then like a sign up popped an advert advertising a sponsored 5k over 10 days. Cancer has affected loved ones and I know would had touched many of you in different ways. I want to support further research and treatment. Help others so no matter how small your donation please give. 

I will be doing this with the support of my husband Rob who is always by my side. We are hoping to complete this challenge with a run for each 5k although the 5k can be walked. 

Thank you for your support.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Throughout this global pandemic, access to cancer support and treatment has never been more stretched. Research shows that the amount of people getting symptoms checked has drastically fallen. This in itself is creating a future cancer pandemic.

With the physical and financial strain that COVID-19 is putting on our health service, people are already having to wait weeks for treatment plans, some are having treatments cancelled and across the country, every single week people are having operations cancelled in what already is the scariest and most difficult time of their lives, before we even talk about a global pandemic and the challenges that brings.

In a time where little fundraising is able to take place due to lockdown restrictions, charity's like Macmillan have never needed our support more.

If you can donate the cost of a packet of Christmas cards or a Christmas drink I'd be extremely grateful. Your donation will help fund Macmillan to continue doing the incredible work they do, and help ensure that every person and their family going through cancer treatment right now, in the middle of a global pandemic, get's access to the physical and emotional help and support they need this Christmas. Thank you xx

story:
Battle Cancer is one day, four nine-minute workouts, one fundraising goal.
Set yourself a challenge, give yourself a purpose and take part in an epic day!
Battle Cancer combines playful functional fitness workouts with a teamwork experience like no other. We're not about finding the strongest or fittest, Battle Cancer is a mindset, a community and battling something bigger than us all.

1. Enter as a team of four (all male, all female, or mixed - any combination of gender: 2 men 2 women, 1 man 3 women, 1 woman 3 men. 

2. Fundraise for Macmillan in the lead up to the competition and submit your fundraising total at registration. This will rank you on the leaderboard for your chance to get a leg up on the competition before any fitness takes place!

3. Compete in four 9-minute fitness workouts over the course of the day

4. End on a huge sense of accomplishment

Whether you are participating in the UK, Europe or America - thank you for playing a part in supporting Macmillan.

pageSummary: I will cycle, walk and run 622 miles over 6 months because they support people when they need it most.
pageSummaryWhat: I will cycle, walk and run 622 miles over 6 months
pageSummaryWhy: they support people when they need it most.
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising efforts. I am raising money as part of my Bronze Duke of Edinburgh challenge. I intend to cover the 622 miles that will take me to Inverness, and home again, by an accumulation of shorter distances covered by walking, running and cycling over the course of 6 months.  My activities will all be tracked on Strava and these are linked to this site, check them out.

I started my challenge in October and intend to complete it by end of March.  

I have chosen Macmillan support because of all the help and care they give to families and individuals when they need it most.  Macmillan nurses have been there to help my family in the past and I want to repay them by helping out financially.

charity.name: St John Ambulance
owner: Warwick University Unit St John Ambulance
story:
This is the fundraising page for Warwick University Unit - St John Ambulance. 

The University of Warwick First Aid Society and St John Ambulance unit work hand in hand to deliver up-to-date first aid Awareness sessions and outreach sessions in the local community. Our first aiders have supported the NHS throughout the Coronavirus pandemic by supporting in hospitals and at blood donation centres. We have volunteered almost 1800 hours of since the first lockdown began and over 2300 hours in total this year. 

How your donation saves lives:

£4: Can give a child a 60-minute first aid lesson in school

£10: Could kit out volunteers with the correct equipment to treat sick or injured people

£15: Can help us keep one of our ambulances on the road serving the community for a day

£25: Allows us to equip someone with the first aid skills to save a life

£40: Could train a volunteer to give first aid at events like football matches and concerts 

£60: Can provide a volunteer with the kit they need to save a life

£100: Can pay for a trainer to deliver training to a class of 32 children

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hello everyone

Saturday 21 November marks 10 years since my Dad sadly passed away to heart disease aged 47. 

His death fundamentally changed the course of my life and those around me.  He was charismatic, charming and positive - I miss his energy, his guidance and his grin.  I’ve learnt that my grief has never really disappeared.  The best case scenario is that it lies dormant.  But then, there will be an occasion (some you expect and some you don’t) where you are hit with an overwhelming sense of sadness.  The best response  I’ve found is to accept that firstly, and then where possible, harness that energy into positive action. 

So, to mark the anniversary, I’m trying to run 24 miles across a 24 hour window.   It’ll be 4 separate runs of 6 miles - running around different areas of London at increasingly slower speeds.  I’ll be stopping and starting again and again - there’s a nice metaphor in there but not one that my legs will appreciate.

I’ve done a few preparatory runs but the training was modest and dull - I’m not convinced anyone really “enjoys” running like you can enjoy chocolate, pizza or cake.  Anyhow, the long and the short of this is, I am overweight and underprepared so this is going to be a challenge to which you should, if you would be so kind, give generously.

A few friends have kindly agreed to run different sections of this mammoth run with me, and I’m hoping that their company will push me on.   It’s also harder to cut the corners or flat out stop if someone else is running alongside…

In a year that completely sucks, I am hoping that I might be able to inject some positivity into what is a sad day for my family.   BHF is a tremendous cause - the facts are that:

  • Heart and circulatory diseases cause more than a quarter of all deaths in the UK. 
  • Around 44,000 people under the age of 75 in the UK die from heart and circulatory diseases each year.

  • Since the BHF was established, the annual number of deaths from heart and circulatory diseases in the UK has fallen by around a half.

If you can donate something to aid the fight against cardiovascular disease,  I would be very grateful.

Thanks

Sam

story:
Help us raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! 

During December hundreds of our fundraising dogs across the UK would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at supermarket and street collections, Christmas fairs and festive coffee mornings. Our four-legged fundraisers support the 400+ fundraising groups across the UK from Glasgow to Plymouth and everywhere in between.

Due to the current situation, most of our fundraising groups will not be out collecting this festive season, and our four-legged fundraisers will be very much missed! We hope you will do your bit and help us as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! Heres how you can join in: 

	Donate £12 and share our posts across social media nominating a friend, family member or colleague to  get involved

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Some of us from work are going to run 5k. We're aiming to do this at the beginning of Feb to allow time for training and working through the Couch to 5k. None of us are runners and some of us won't even run for a bus so it is going to be a challenge.

We would like to raise money for Cancer Research UK and Bedford Hospital (separate page) because too many people are affected by cancer.

Cancer affects 1 in 2 of us which is a ridiculous statistic in itself, but knowing that if you're in the unlucky 50% you will be in pain, have nausea/sickness and feel like hell to just get better..... that if it's treatable is insane. We need to find a more bearable treatment.

Covid has put a stop to so much fund raising resulting in halting trails and potentially prolonging new treatments for many years which is why raising money for Cancer Research UK is so important.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

From the very start of when our Dad's health began to fail, his only wish was that he could die at home, where he had raised his family, where he felt most comfortable and where our families happiest of memories resided.

As a family we did all we could to make this wish come true, but without the help of Marie Curie, it simply wouldn't have been possible. In fact all the help we received was beyond our expectations and we will never be able to fully thank all the people involved in looking after him during the last few months of his life.

In honour of our Dad and in honour of all the people that helped make his wish come true, please give generously...

story:

Thank you.

pageSummary: We're a group of friends walking in January 2021 because we love UK wildlife & the Land for Life campaign!
pageSummaryWhat: We're a group of friends walking in January 2021
pageSummaryWhy: we love UK wildlife & the Land for Life campaign!
story:
IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... 

You might notice there's less wildlife than there used to be.  That's because half of all UK species are in decline - we're losing our precious red squirrels, hares, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate.  By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, we are reconnecting with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it.  The funds we raise will help WWF campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world.  

Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back. 

This winter, you can make your donations go even further with the Government’s UK Aid Match programme. Donate before 2 February 2021 and the UK Government will match all public donations to support WWF's Land For Life project, up to £2 million.

The Land for Life project focuses on securing livelihoods and supporting Maasai communities, while restoring wildlife in critical corridors. Through this project, we’re collaborating with communities in southern Kenya and northern Tanzania to help keep landscapes healthy and develop solutions for people and wildlife to coexist and thrive.

Your donations will support WWF’s vital work around the world, while match funds from the UK Government will go towards our Land for Life appeal.

Thank you from all of us!

By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

story:
Throughout this pandemic the one constant was the access to lovely walks outside. It has made us realise it is more important than ever to protect our wildlife. So this year to celebrate Mum's birthday in January we are going to take a walk, and see how much wildlife we meet. We would love to think that you too are joining our celebration, and going for a walk too. If you are walking with children ask me about the resources I've received to make the walk even more fun. Any donations you wish to make to WWF for Mum's birthday would be much appreciated though your good wishes are enough if you prefer. Donations will be match funded so you could make a real difference.

Message from WWF:

IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. story: Could you go 24 hours without food and be expected to live a normal healthy life? This is a challenge faced daily for approximately 11.3% of the world's population including children. Every minute, more than five child mortalities can be attributed to malnutrition. For those fortunate to survive, malnutrition has detrimental effects on childhood growth and learning abilities. Through FAST 24, Lancaster University students will go without food on 27th November to raise money for UNICEF's emergency food programmes. The United Nation's International Children's Emergency UNICEF is a charity part of the United Nation's Development Group committed to protection of children worldwide. UNICEF provides 80% of the world's life-saving food through its nutrition programmes. With your help, we can help increase access to good nutrition to children worldwide giving them a healthier, happier life.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This is a run I've wanted to do the last 3 years, I've finally for the opportunity to do it. It may well wreck me but gonna have some fun.

https://www.runningcalendar.co.nz/event/toi-challenge/

Tois Challenge 18km course follows the 'Nga Tapuwai o Toi' track, which literally means 'In the Footsteps of Toi', after the Maori chief Toi who ruled the area some 800 years ago. The trail twists up and down steep coastal hills and along two beautiful beaches, through stunning bush, up and down hundreds of steps, eased by stunning views of the sparkling Pacific Ocean and distant islands.

Thanks for considering supporting a good cause :)

Owen C

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
